        // ── Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided (Article) ─────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided",
            Slug = "vendors-create-quick-vs-guided",
            Summary = "The New Vendor fork: when to use Quick add versus the 5-step Guided setup wizard, and what each path captures.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors","/vendors/new"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","procurement","onboarding"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided\n\nClicking **+ New Vendor** on the Vendors page no longer drops you straight into a form — it opens a small **fork dialog** that asks *how* you want to set up the vendor. There are two paths, and choosing the right one saves rework later.\n\n### The fork dialog\n\nThe fork shows two cards:\n\n- **Quick add** (badged *Fast*) — \"Just the essentials — company name and basic contact. Flesh out the rest later.\" This is the dominant, everyday path.\n- **Guided setup** — \"Step-by-step for strategic or approved vendors — classification, address, terms, and the parts they supply.\"\n\nClick a card to choose; the **Cancel** button at the bottom backs out without creating anything.\n\n### Quick add — the everyday path\n\nQuick add opens the flat vendor dialog. The only required field is **Company Name**; contact name, email, phone, address, payment terms, and notes are all optional and can be filled in later. Use Quick add when:\n\n- You just need the vendor to exist so you can put it on a purchase order.\n- It is a one-off or low-volume transactional supplier.\n- You will enrich the record later (or let an accounting sync fill in the details).\n\nThe vendor is created immediately and becomes available in PO vendor dropdowns. You can always open the vendor later and add an address, terms, or catalog parts.\n\n### Guided setup — for strategic / approved vendors\n\nChoosing **Guided setup** routes you to a dedicated wizard at **/vendors/new** built on the shared guided-workflow shell (the same framework Parts uses). It is worth the extra effort for strategic suppliers, approved-vendor-list (AVL) partners, or any vendor whose address, terms, and supplied parts you want captured up front. The wizard walks five steps:\n\n1. **Identity** *(required)* — Company name, contact name, email, and phone. This is the step that actually creates (materializes) the vendor row, so company name is required here. Until you complete Identity, nothing is saved.\n2. **Address** *(optional)* — Street, city, state, ZIP, and country for the vendor's remit-to / ship-from address.\n3. **Terms** *(optional)* — Payment terms (Net 30, etc.) and related billing settings.\n4. **Supply Items** *(optional)* — A pointer step. Vendor-part catalog entries (the parts this vendor supplies, with their AVL/preferred flags and pricing) are added on the vendor's **Catalog** tab after the vendor exists — the wizard reminds you to do that rather than forcing bulk entry mid-wizard.\n5. **Review** *(required)* — A final summary; confirm to finish.\n\n### Express vs Guided mode inside the wizard\n\nThe workflow shell has a **mode toggle**. *Guided* mode shows one step at a time with rationale available in a side panel; *Express* mode collapses the optional steps into a single consolidated screen for users who already know what they're entering. Both modes hit the same steps and the same required gates (Identity + Review).\n\n### URL is the source of truth\n\nThe wizard keeps its state in the URL (`?workflow=vendor-guided-v1&step=…&mode=…`). After the Identity step materializes the vendor, the route upgrades from `/vendors/new` to `/vendors/{id}` so you can bookmark, share, or resume a half-finished setup — reopening that URL drops you back where you left off.\n\n### Which should I pick?\n\n| Situation | Path |\n|---|---|\n| Need the vendor on a PO right now | Quick add |\n| One-off or low-volume supplier | Quick add |\n| Strategic / sole-source / AVL partner | Guided setup |\n| You want address + terms + supplied parts captured up front | Guided setup |\n| Importing many vendor-supplied parts | Guided setup, then bulk CSV import on the Catalog tab |\n\nThere is no \"convert from lead\" path for vendors (leads become customers, not suppliers), so the fork is two-way rather than three-way.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Vendor Catalog & AVL (Article) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Vendor Catalog & Approved Vendor List (AVL)",
            Slug = "vendors-catalog-avl",
            Summary = "The Catalog tab on a vendor: the parts a vendor supplies, the Approved (AVL) and Preferred Source flags, bulk CSV import, and how it ties into purchasing.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","catalog","avl","procurement","vendor-parts"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Vendor Catalog & Approved Vendor List (AVL)\n\nEvery vendor detail panel has a **Catalog** tab. This is where you record the **parts a vendor supplies** — the vendor-part relationship that links a Part in your catalog to a Vendor, with vendor-scoped sourcing details. It is the supply side of the same data you see on a Part's **Sources** tab; the Catalog tab just looks at it from the vendor's point of view (\"what does *this vendor* sell us?\").\n\n### Opening the Catalog tab\n\nFrom the Vendors list, click a vendor row to open its detail panel, then click the **Catalog** tab (next to Info, Purchase Orders, and Scorecard). The tab loads the list of vendor-parts for that vendor.\n\n### What a vendor-part row holds\n\nEach catalog row is one part this vendor can supply, with vendor-specific fields:\n\n- **Part** — the part number and name from your Parts catalog.\n- **Vendor Part Number** — the vendor's own SKU / catalog number for the part.\n- **Vendor MPN** — the manufacturer part number when the vendor is a distributor reselling someone else's part (distinct from the part's own engineering MPN).\n- **Lead Time (days)**, **Min Order Qty (MOQ)**, **Pack Size** — vendor-scoped procurement parameters.\n- **Country of Origin** and **HTS Code** — trade-compliance fields.\n- **Price tiers** — quantity-break pricing (covered in the *Managing Vendor Pricing* module).\n- **Approved** and **Preferred** flags — see below.\n- **Notes** and **Last Quoted Date**.\n\n### The Approved flag (AVL)\n\nThe **Approved** toggle is your **Approved Vendor List (AVL)** marker. An approved vendor-part means \"this vendor is cleared to supply this part\" — it has passed whatever qualification your shop requires. In the list, approved rows show a green **check_circle** icon; un-approved rows show a **block** icon. Purchasing uses this flag to steer buyers toward qualified sources.\n\n### The Preferred Source flag\n\nThe **Preferred** toggle marks the *go-to* source for a part. Preferred rows show a filled **star**; you can toggle it directly from the catalog list using the star button. There is a hard invariant: **at most one vendor-part per Part may be Preferred at a time.** Setting Preferred on one source automatically clears it on every other vendor for that same part — so the \"preferred source\" question always has exactly one answer. The preferred vendor-part also feeds the Part's snapshot of lead time / MOQ / pack size that replenishment and auto-PO read.\n\n### Adding, editing, and removing catalog entries\n\n- **+ Add** opens the vendor-part form dialog. The vendor is locked (you're already inside that vendor), so you pick the **Part** and fill in the vendor-scoped fields, including the Approved and Preferred toggles.\n- The **edit** (pencil) row action reopens the same form to change any field.\n- The **delete** (trash) row action removes the part from this vendor's catalog. This unlinks the vendor-part relationship; it does not delete the Part itself.\n- The **Is Manufacturer** toggle on the form tells the system the vendor *is* the manufacturer (so the manufacturer name derives from the vendor and you enter a single part number) versus a distributor (where you record both a vendor part number and the manufacturer's MPN).\n\n### Bulk CSV import\n\nFor onboarding a distributor's catalog or a long price list, use **Import** (the upload_file button at the top of the Catalog tab). The flow is a two-state dialog:\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag-and-drop or browse for a `.csv`. A **Download template** link gives you the exact column layout.\n2. **Preview** — the system parses the file and shows every row tagged as **Add**, **Update**, or **Error**, with a summary count. Rows that fail validation are flagged with an error message and the **Apply** button stays disabled until the errors are resolved (you fix the CSV and re-import).\n\nApplying commits the adds and updates in one pass. Import matches on part number, so existing vendor-parts are updated rather than duplicated.\n\n### How the catalog feeds purchasing\n\nThe vendor-part catalog is definitional master data that downstream purchasing reads:\n\n- **Replenishment & Auto-PO** look at the preferred source and its lead time / MOQ / pricing to suggest reorders.\n- **Purchase Orders** pull the vendor's part number and tiered price when you add a line for a part this vendor supplies.\n- The **AVL (Approved) flag** keeps buyers ordering from qualified sources.\n\nBecause it is master data, edits to a vendor-part are recorded on **both** the Vendor's and the Part's activity logs (the vendor-part sits at the indexing point between them).","sections":[]}"""
        });

