        // ── Managing Vendor Pricing — Price Tiers (Article) ──────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Managing Vendor Pricing — Price Tiers",
            Slug = "vendors-price-tiers",
            Summary = "Quantity-break price tiers on a vendor-part: how tiers are picked, currency, effective dating, viewing tier history, and how purchasing resolves a price.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","pricing","price-tiers","procurement","vendor-parts"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Managing Vendor Pricing — Price Tiers\n\nVendors rarely quote a single flat price — they quote **quantity breaks**: cheaper per-unit as you buy more. Forge captures this with **price tiers** on each vendor-part. A tier is a row that says \"at this minimum quantity (and on/after this date), the unit price is X in this currency.\"\n\n### Opening the price-tiers dialog\n\nOn a vendor's **Catalog** tab, the **Price Tiers** column shows the lowest current price plus a small count badge of how many tiers exist. Click that price (or the **price_change** action on the inline single-source card) to open the **Price Tiers** dialog for that vendor-part. The dialog lists the existing tiers and has an **Add Tier** form at the bottom.\n\n### What a tier holds\n\n- **Min Quantity** *(required)* — the lowest order quantity at which this tier's price applies. The tier with the largest Min Quantity that is still ≤ your order quantity wins.\n- **Unit Price** *(required)* — the per-unit price at that break.\n- **Currency** *(required)* — the price's currency. Tiers can be quoted in different currencies; purchasing converts as needed.\n- **Effective From / Effective To** *(optional)* — the date window the tier is valid. Leave Effective To blank for \"current, no end date.\" This is how you stage a future price change without losing the old price.\n- **Option (purchase unit)** — when the part has multiple purchase units, the tier can be scoped to one; a per-base preview shows the equivalent price per base unit.\n- **Notes** *(optional)*.\n\n### How a price is resolved\n\nWhen purchasing needs a price for a quantity, it picks the tier whose **Min Quantity ≤ requested quantity** with the highest such Min Quantity, among tiers whose **effective date window** contains the order date. That is the per-unit price used on the PO line. If you order below the lowest tier's Min Quantity, the lowest tier still applies as the floor price (and the system can warn about below-minimum or off-tier ordering).\n\n### Quantity-break example\n\n| Min Qty | Unit Price |\n|---|---|\n| 1 | $2.00 |\n| 100 | $1.60 |\n| 500 | $1.35 |\n\n- Order 50 → $2.00 each (the qty-1 tier; no higher tier reached yet).\n- Order 250 → $1.60 each (qty-100 tier wins; 500 not reached).\n- Order 1,000 → $1.35 each (qty-500 tier wins).\n\n### Effective dating and price history\n\nTiers are **append-and-supersede**, not edit-in-place — you add a new tier (often with a future Effective From) rather than overwriting an old price, which preserves what you actually paid historically. To review past pricing, use the **history** (clock) action on a catalog row to open the **Price Tier History** — the change log of tiers added and removed over time. This is what lets the vendor scorecard compute average price variance and what auditors use to see when a price moved.\n\n### Adding and removing tiers\n\n- Fill the **Add Tier** form (Min Quantity, Unit Price, Currency, optional dates and notes) and click **Add Tier**. The dialog's primary action is *Add Tier*; the left button is **Close** (closing does not commit an unfinished row — only Add Tier commits).\n- Remove a tier with its **delete** row action. Because history is preserved, removing a tier records the removal rather than erasing the fact it existed.\n\n### Where tiers show up downstream\n\n- The Catalog/Sources list shows the **lowest current tier** as the headline price.\n- **Purchase Order** lines auto-fill the resolved tiered price for the ordered quantity.\n- **Replenishment / Auto-PO** use the preferred source's pricing in reorder math.\n- The **Scorecard's Price (20%)** factor compares actual PO prices against expected tier pricing to compute price variance.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Catalog & Pricing Knowledge Check (Quiz) ─────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
