            Summary = "Test your knowledge of the vendor Catalog/AVL tab, Approved and Preferred flags, bulk import, price tiers, and the Quick-vs-Guided create fork.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 9,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","quiz","catalog","avl","pricing","procurement"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":7,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"vc1","text":"You click + New Vendor to add a strategic, sole-source supplier and want to capture its address, payment terms, and the parts it supplies up front. Which path should you choose in the fork dialog?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Quick add — it captures everything in one flat form"},{"id":"b","text":"Guided setup — the 5-step wizard at /vendors/new for strategic or approved vendors","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Convert from Lead — promote the supplier lead to a vendor"},{"id":"d","text":"There is no fork; New Vendor always opens the same dialog"}],"explanation":"The New Vendor fork offers Quick add (essentials only, fastest) and Guided setup. For a strategic or approved (AVL) supplier where you want classification, address, terms, and supplied parts captured up front, choose Guided setup — it routes to the 5-step wizard at /vendors/new (Identity, Address, Terms, Supply Items, Review). There is no convert-from-lead path for vendors."},{"id":"vc2","text":"In the Guided vendor wizard, which step actually creates (materializes) the vendor record, and is therefore required?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Address"},{"id":"b","text":"Terms"},{"id":"c","text":"Identity (company name + contact)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Supply Items"}],"explanation":"The Identity step (company name, contact name, email, phone) materializes the vendor row, so company name is required there. Until Identity is completed, nothing is saved. Address, Terms, and Supply Items are optional; Review is the required final confirmation."},{"id":"vc3","text":"On a vendor's Catalog tab, what does the Approved (green check_circle) flag on a vendor-part represent?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The vendor-part has been synced from QuickBooks"},{"id":"b","text":"The vendor is cleared to supply this part — the Approved Vendor List (AVL) marker","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The part has at least one price tier defined"},{"id":"d","text":"The purchase order for this part has been approved"}],"explanation":"The Approved toggle is the Approved Vendor List (AVL) marker: this vendor is qualified/cleared to supply this part. Approved rows show a green check_circle; un-approved rows show a block icon. Purchasing uses it to steer buyers toward qualified sources. It is unrelated to accounting sync, pricing, or PO approval."},{"id":"vc4","text":"You set the Preferred (star) flag on Vendor A for Part X. Vendor B was previously the preferred source for Part X. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Both Vendor A and Vendor B are now preferred for Part X"},{"id":"b","text":"Vendor B's Preferred flag is automatically cleared — at most one vendor-part per part can be Preferred","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The system blocks the change until you manually unset Vendor B"},{"id":"d","text":"Part X is removed from Vendor B's catalog entirely"}],"explanation":"There is a hard invariant: at most one vendor-part per Part may be Preferred at a time. Setting Preferred on Vendor A automatically clears it on every other vendor for that part (including Vendor B), so the 'preferred source' question always has exactly one answer. Vendor B keeps the part in its catalog — only the Preferred flag moves."},{"id":"vc5","text":"A vendor-part has price tiers of $2.00 at min qty 1, $1.60 at min qty 100, and $1.35 at min qty 500. What unit price applies to an order of 250 units?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"$2.00 — the base tier always applies"},{"id":"b","text":"$1.60 — the qty-100 tier wins because 100 ≤ 250 < 500","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"$1.35 — the lowest available price always applies"},{"id":"d","text":"An average of the three tiers"}],"explanation":"Price resolution picks the tier with the highest Min Quantity that is still ≤ the requested quantity. For 250 units, the qty-100 tier ($1.60) wins because 100 ≤ 250 but the qty-500 tier isn't reached. Order 1,000 and the qty-500 tier ($1.35) would win."},{"id":"vc6","text":"You need to onboard a distributor's full catalog of parts they supply, with vendor part numbers and lead times. What's the most efficient way?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Add each part one at a time with the + Add button"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Import button on the Catalog tab: download the template, fill the CSV, then review the Add/Update/Error preview and Apply","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Enter all the parts during the Supply Items step of the guided wizard"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a purchase order — receiving will auto-create the vendor-parts"}],"explanation":"The Catalog tab's Import button handles bulk onboarding. Download the template for the exact columns, fill the CSV, and the two-state dialog shows a preview tagging each row Add, Update, or Error with a summary. Apply stays disabled until errors are fixed. Import matches on part number, so existing entries update rather than duplicate. The Supply Items wizard step is just a pointer to do this on the Catalog tab afterward."},{"id":"vc7","text":"Why are price tiers added-and-superseded (with effective dates) rather than edited in place, and where do you review past pricing?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They aren't — editing a tier overwrites the price with no record kept"},{"id":"b","text":"To preserve price history; you review it via the history (clock) action which opens the Price Tier History","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Because tiers are read-only once a PO is placed"},{"id":"d","text":"Price history lives only in QuickBooks after a sync"}],"explanation":"Tiers are append-and-supersede so the record of what you actually paid is preserved — you add a new tier (often with a future Effective From) instead of overwriting. The history (clock) action on a catalog row opens the Price Tier History change log. This preserved history feeds the scorecard's average price-variance calculation."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Vendors — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "vendors-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case and power-user reference: off-tier variance override, the performance comparison report, completeness chips, CSV import, the manufacturer toggle, preferred-uniqueness, and draft auto-save.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Off-Tier Variance % Override\n\nWhen a PO line is priced away from the vendor-part's effective price tier, purchasing raises an **off-tier prompt**. The threshold that decides \"how far is too far\" resolves in three steps (`CheckTierVarianceQuery`):\n\n1. **Per-vendor override** — `Vendor.OffTierVariancePct` (nullable). Set it on the vendor dialog's `offTierVariancePct` field (validated `min(0)`). When present, it wins.\n2. **System setting** — the `purchasing.offTierVariancePct` SystemSetting, used when the vendor override is null.\n3. **Fallback** — 5% (`FallbackThresholdPct`) when neither is set.\n\nVariance is computed per line as `abs((enteredUnitPrice - tierUnitPrice) / tierUnitPrice) * 100`, matched against the same purchase option (`PurchaseUnitId`) and the largest qualifying `MinQuantity` break. A line is flagged off-tier when variance exceeds the resolved threshold. Edge cases: a zero tier price makes any non-zero entered price off-tier; if the VendorPart exists but has no effective tier, or no VendorPart row exists at all, the line is treated as off-tier so the prompt can offer to create the first tier. The same resolver backs the AI-assisted price-override review (`ReviewPriceOverride`), which bands a risk level (Low / Medium / High; >25% variance = High).\n\n## Vendor Performance Comparison Report\n\n`GET /api/v1/vendors/performance-report?dateFrom=&dateTo=` returns a ranked cross-vendor comparison (`GetVendorPerformanceReportQuery` to `List<VendorComparisonRowModel>`). It runs each **active** vendor's scorecard for the window and returns one row per vendor: `VendorId`, `VendorName`, `OnTimePercent`, `QualityPercent`, `TotalSpend`, `OverallScore`, `Grade`, and `Trend`. Defaults: `dateTo` = today, `dateFrom` = 12 months prior. **Trend** compares this period's overall score against the immediately-preceding period of equal length (looks up a stored `VendorScorecard` for the prior window); when no prior scorecard exists, trend is 0. Rows are sorted by `OverallScore` descending — the leaderboard. This is the cross-vendor counterpart to the single-vendor Scorecard tab.\n\n## Entity-Completeness Chips\n\nThe vendor detail panel header renders `<app-entity-completeness-chip entityType=\"Vendor\" [entityId]=\"vendor.id\" />`. The chip summarizes whether the vendor satisfies the field requirements of every currently-enabled capability:\n\n- **Green dot + \"Ready\"** — all enabled capabilities with declared requirements pass (also the state when the install has declared no requirements at all).\n- **Amber chip + \"Incomplete for N\"** — at least one capability fails; clicking opens a CDK overlay popover with the per-capability missing-fields breakdown (e.g. \"Tax ID\", \"Payment Terms\"), each with a fuller tooltip.\n\nCompleteness is capability-driven config, not hard validation — a vendor can be fully usable yet \"Incomplete for N\" if a capability you enabled wants fields this vendor hasn't filled. The chip and its inline `<app-entity-completeness-badge>` sibling share one `EntityCompletenessService` cache, so rendering both for a row fires a single network call. On a service error the chip renders nothing (rather than a misleading \"Ready\").\n\n## CSV Import Format & Errors\n\nThe Catalog (vendor-parts) bulk **Import** is a two-state dialog. Columns (from the Download-template link / `vendor-part-bulk-import-dialog`): `partNumber, vendorPartNumber, manufacturerName, vendorMpn, leadTimeDays, minOrderQty, packSize, countryOfOrigin, htsCode, notes`. Flow:\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag-drop or browse a `.csv`.\n2. **Preview** — every parsed row is tagged **Add**, **Update**, or **Error** with a summary count. Matching is by `partNumber` against the vendor's existing catalog, so a known part becomes **Update** (not a duplicate) and an unknown one becomes **Add**.\n\nRows failing validation are tagged **Error** with a message; the **Apply** button stays disabled until every error is resolved — fix the CSV and re-import. Apply commits all adds and updates in one pass.\n\n## Vendor-Is-Manufacturer Toggle\n\nOn the vendor-part form the **Is Manufacturer** toggle (`isManufacturer`) declares the vendor's role for that part:\n\n- **On** — the vendor *is* the manufacturer. The manufacturer name derives from the vendor and you enter a single part number; no separate MPN.\n- **Off (distributor)** — the vendor resells someone else's part. You record both the **Vendor Part Number** (the distributor's SKU) and the **Vendor MPN** / `manufacturerName` (the original manufacturer's identity). This `VendorMpn` is distinct from the Part's own engineering `ManufacturerPartNumber`.\n\nThe toggle changes which identity fields the form expects, keeping single-source (manufacturer) and resold (distributor) supply rows unambiguous.\n\n## Preferred-Uniqueness & Sole-Source Rendering\n\nA hard invariant governs the **Preferred** (sole-source / star) flag: **at most one VendorPart per Part may have `IsPreferred = true`**. Setting it on one source automatically clears it on every other vendor for that same Part inside one SaveChanges (enforced in both CreateVendorPart and UpdateVendorPart) — so \"the preferred source\" always has exactly one answer. `preferred-vendor-changed` is logged as an activity verb when it moves.\n\nThe preferred VendorPart also feeds `Part.PreferredVendorId` plus the `Part.MinOrderQty` / `Part.PackSize` / `Part.LeadTimeDays` snapshot that replenishment and auto-PO read. Rendering: in the Catalog/Sources list the preferred row shows a filled **star** (toggle directly via the star button); a single-source part renders as an inline single-source card rather than the multi-row table.\n\n## Draft Auto-Save\n\nThe flat vendor dialog (`VendorDialogComponent`) participates in the global Draft system via a `draftConfig` of `{ entityType: 'vendor', entityId: <id or 'new'>, route: '/vendors' }`. Dirty form state auto-saves to IndexedDB (debounced ~2.5s), survives logout / crash / token expiry, and is offered back via the post-login recovery prompt and per-form recovery banner. Drafts clear only on explicit discard, successful save (`clearDraft()` on save), or TTL expiry. The guided wizard does **not** use this form-draft mechanism — it persists step-by-step server-side and keeps resumable state in the URL (`?workflow=vendor-guided-v1&step=...`), upgrading `/vendors/new` to `/vendors/{id}` once Identity materializes the row.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Vendors training modules");
